  "final_text": "The analysis is clear. Here are my findings:\n\n```json\n[\n  {\n    \"title\": \"Proxy-Authorization header leaked to different proxy on redirect\",\n    \"category\": \"security\",\n    \"severity\": \"critical\",\n    \"confidence\": 0.97,\n    \"file\": \"requests/sessions.py\",\n    \"start_line\": 317,\n    \"end_line\": 328,\n    \"evidence\": [\n      \"Lines 318-319: The two lines `if \\\"Proxy-Authorization\\\" in headers: del headers[\\\"Proxy-Authorization\\\"]` were removed\",\n      \"Line 245: `rebuild_proxies` is called on every redirect in the `resolve_redirects` loop\",\n      \"Line 317: `new_proxies = resolve_proxies(prepared_request, proxies, self.trust_env)` \u2014 the proxy may change on redirect\",\n      \"Lines 327-328: New Proxy-Authorization is only set for non-HTTPS with credentials; otherwise the OLD header persists\",\n      \"Lines 283-296: `rebuild_auth` has `should_strip_auth` for Authorization headers, but no equivalent exists for Proxy-Authorization\"\n    ],\n    \"risk\": \"When a request is redirected and the proxy changes (e.g., due to NO_PROXY rules or environment variable resolution), the Proxy-Authorization header containing credentials for the original proxy is forwarded to the new proxy server. An attacker who controls a redirect target or a downstream proxy can harvest proxy credentials meant for a different proxy. This is a credential leakage vulnerability similar to CVE-2014-1829.\",\n    \"suggested_fix\": \"Restore the deleted lines. Before the `try` block at line 320, re-add:\\n```python\\nif \\\"Proxy-Authorization\\\" in headers:\\n    del headers[\\\"Proxy-Authorization\\\"]\\n```\\nThis ensures stale proxy credentials are always cleared before potentially setting fresh ones for the new proxy.\"\n  }\n]\n```",
